---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getOrderedChapters, chapterLabel } from '../utils/chapters';

const chapters = await getOrderedChapters();
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (path: string) => `${base.replace(/\/$/, '')}/${path.replace(/^\//, '')}`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Amplifier Resolve — Masterclass">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Amplifier Resolve — Masterclass</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">An Operating System for Autonomous Work — Architecture, Contracts, and Design.</p>

    <p>
      A first-principles → implementation → future reading of <strong>Amplifier Resolve</strong>:
      the platform that turns a request (&ldquo;resolve this issue&rdquo;) into an isolated,
      observable, long-lived run of a pluggable resolver — and delivers a pull request at the
      other end. Where the Amplifier Core masterclass explains the <em>harness</em> that a single
      AI session plugs into, this one explains the <em>platform that runs many harnesses at once</em>,
      under isolation, on behalf of the outside world.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={href('diagrams/architecture-map.svg')} alt="Amplifier Resolve architecture map: bridge → platform → resolver containers → SPA." />
      <figcaption>The whole stack at a glance — bridge → platform daemon → resolver containers → SPA (see Chapter 2).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <div class="callout">
      <span class="label">The through-line</span>
      <p><strong>The platform provides mechanism. The resolver provides policy.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>
      Amplifier Core&rsquo;s central idea is <em>mechanism, not policy</em>: the kernel fires events;
      modules decide what happens. Resolve inherits that idea and lifts it one layer up. The platform
      owns the lifecycle, the isolation boundary, the transport, and structural validation. The
      resolver owns the <em>strategy</em> — what to ask for, what the work means, and how to do it
      correctly. Everything in this masterclass is a consequence of holding that line.
    </p>

    <p>
      The signature device is the <strong>Design Decision</strong> callout — a one-sentence statement
      of a choice the platform makes, followed by <em>why the alternative is worse</em>. If you
      remember nothing else, remember the Design Decisions. Cross-references use <code>§</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-sans);border-bottom:1px solid var(--rule);padding-bottom:0.3rem;">
    Table of contents
  </h2>
  <ol class="toc-grid">
    {
      chapters.map((ch) => {
        const lbl = chapterLabel(ch);
        return (
          <li>
            <a href={href(`chapters/${ch.id}`)}>
              <span class="num">{lbl === 'Appendix' ? 'A' : lbl}</span>
              <span class="title">{ch.data.title}</span>
            </a>
          </li>
        );
      })
    }
  </ol>
</BaseLayout>
